\entry{baptestini_role_2013}{article}{}
  \name{author}{3}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Baptestini}{B.}%
     {Elizabeth~M.}{E.~M.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Aguiar}{A.}%
     {Marcus A. M.~de}{M.~A. M.~d.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Bar-Yam}{B.-Y.}%
     {Yaneer}{Y.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{assortative mating, Biodiversity patterns, Neutral speciation, Plant
  Sciences, Sex separation, Theoretical Ecology/Statistics, Zoology}
  \strng{namehash}{BEMAMAMdBYY1}
  \strng{fullhash}{BEMAMAMdBYY1}
  \field{labelyear}{2013}
  \field{extrayear}{1}
  \field{sortinit}{B}
  \field{abstract}{%
  Neutral speciation mechanisms based on isolation by distance and assortative
  mating, termed topopatric, has recently been shown to describe the observed
  patterns of abundance distributions and speciesâ€“area relationships.
  Previous works have considered this type of process only in the context of
  hermaphroditic populations. In this work, we extend a hermaphroditic model of
  topopatric speciation to populations where individuals are explicitly
  separated into males and females. We show that for a particular carrying
  capacity, speciation occurs under similar conditions, but the number of
  species generated is lower than in the hermaphroditic case. As a consequence,
  the speciesâ€“area curve has lower exponents, especially at intermediate
  scales. Evolution results in fewer species having more abundant populations.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
