\entry{cacho_caribbean_2012}{article}{}
  \name{author}{2}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Cacho}{C.}%
     {N.~IvalÃº}{N.~I.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Baum}{B.}%
     {David~A.}{D.~A.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{Biogeography, nuclear gene, Phylogeny, phylogeography, Reproductive
  isolation, speciation}
  \strng{namehash}{CNIBDA1}
  \strng{fullhash}{CNIBDA1}
  \field{labelyear}{2012}
  \field{sortinit}{C}
  \field{abstract}{%
  A ring species arises when a parental population expands around an area of
  unsuitable habitat in such a way that when the two fronts meet they behave as
  distinct species while still being connected through a series of intergrading
  populations. Ring species offer great possibilities for studying the forces
  causing species divergence (e.g. the nature of pre-zygotic or post-zygotic
  reproductive isolation) or helping to maintain species integrity (e.g.
  reinforcement). Yet, ring species are extremely rare, and have only been
  documented convincingly in animals. Here, we present phylogenetic analyses of
  two nuclear gene regions from the Caribbean slipper spurge (Euphorbia
  tithymaloides) species complex that provide evidence that this group forms a
  ring species. These data show that the species complex originated in the area
  where Mexico and Guatemala meet, and expanded around the Caribbean basin
  along two distinct fronts: one eastward through the Yucatan Peninsula and
  into the Greater Antilles ({GA}); one southeastward through northern South
  America and then northward to the Lesser Antilles and eastern {GA}. The two
  terminal forms co-occur in the Virgin Islands and appear to be
  morphologically and ecologically distinct. Thus, our results suggest that
  Euphorbia tithymaloides is the first compelling example of a ring species in
  plants.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1098/rspb.2012.0498
  \endverb
  \field{issn}{0962-8452, 1471-2954}
  \field{number}{1742}
  \field{pages}{3377\bibrangedash 3383}
  \field{shorttitle}{The Caribbean slipper spurge Euphorbia tithymaloides}
  \field{title}{The Caribbean slipper spurge \textit{Euphorbia tithymaloides}:
  the first example of a ring species in plants}
  \verb{url}
  \verb http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/279/1742/3377
  \endverb
  \field{volume}{279}
  \verb{file}
  \verb Full Text PDF:/home/ayana/.mozilla/firefox/b7fuqjsf.default/zotero/stor
  \verb age/6AACHKHJ/Cacho and Baum - 2012 - The Caribbean slipper spurge Eupho
  \verb rbia tithymaloid.pdf:application/pdf;Snapshot:/home/ayana/.mozilla/fire
  \verb fox/b7fuqjsf.default/zotero/storage/JDEJBAUZ/3377.html:text/html
  \endverb
  \field{journaltitle}{Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences}
  \field{month}{09}
  \field{year}{2012}
  \field{urlday}{05}
  \field{urlmonth}{10}
  \field{urlyear}{2013}
