\entry{kuchta_closing_2009}{article}{}
  \name{author}{4}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Kuchta}{K.}%
     {Shawn~R.}{S.~R.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Parks}{P.}%
     {Duncan~S.}{D.~S.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Mueller}{M.}%
     {Rachel~Lockridge}{R.~L.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Wake}{W.}%
     {David~B.}{D.~B.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{Bayesian analysis, Biogeography, California, geomorphology,
  mitochondrial {DNA}, phylogeography, speciation, species concepts}
  \strng{namehash}{KSR+1}
  \strng{fullhash}{KSRPDSMRLWDB1}
  \field{labelyear}{2009}
  \field{sortinit}{K}
  \field{abstract}{%
  Aimâ€‚ The salamander Ensatina eschscholtzii Gray is a classic example of a
  ring species, or a species that has expanded around a central barrier to form
  a secondary contact characterized by species-level divergence. In the
  original formulation of the ring species scenario, an explicit
  biogeographical model was proposed to account for the occurrence of
  intraspecific sympatry between two subspecies in southern California (the
  â€˜southern closureâ€™ model). Here we develop an alternative ring species
  model that is informed by the geomorphological development of the California
  Coast Ranges, and which situates the point of ring closure in the Monterey
  Bay region of central coastal California (the â€˜Monterey closureâ€™ model).
  Our study has two aims. The first is to use phylogenetic methods to evaluate
  the two competing biogeographical models. The second is to describe patterns
  of phylogeographical diversity throughout the range of the Ensatina complex,
  and to compare these patterns with previously published molecular systematic
  data. Locationâ€‚ Western North America, with a focus on the state of
  California, {USA}. Methodsâ€‚ We obtained mitochondrial {DNA} sequence data
  from 385 individuals from 224 populations. A phylogeny was inferred using
  Bayesian techniques, and the geographical distributions of haplotypes and
  clades were mapped. The two biogeographical ring species models were tested
  against our Bayesian topology, including the associated Bayesian 95\%
  credible set of trees. Resultsâ€‚ High levels of phylogeographical diversity
  were revealed, especially in central coastal and northern California. Our
  Bayesian topology contradicts the Monterey closure model; however, 0.08\% of
  the trees in our Bayesian 95\% credible set are consistent with this model.
  In contrast, the classic ring species biogeographical model (the southern
  closure model) is consistent with our Bayesian topology, as were 99.92\% of
  the trees in our 95\% credible set. Main conclusionsâ€‚ Our Bayesian
  phylogenetic analysis most strongly supports the classic ring species model,
  modified to accommodate an improved understanding of the complex
  geomorphological evolution of the California Coast Ranges. In addition, high
  levels of phylogeographical diversity in central and northern California were
  identified, which is consistent with the striking levels of allozymic
  differentiation reported previously from those regions.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1111/j.1365-2699.2008.02052.x
  \endverb
  \field{issn}{1365-2699}
  \field{number}{5}
  \field{pages}{982\bibrangedash 995}
  \field{shorttitle}{Closing the ring}
  \field{title}{Closing the ring: historical biogeography of the salamander
  ring species \textit{Ensatina eschscholtzii}}
