\entry{lande_models_1981}{article}{}
  \name{author}{1}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Lande}{L.}%
     {Russell}{R.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{genetic correlation, mating preferences, runaway process, sexual
  dimorphism}
  \strng{namehash}{LR1}
  \strng{fullhash}{LR1}
  \field{labelyear}{1981}
  \field{sortinit}{L}
  \field{abstract}{%
  The joint evolution of female mating preferences and secondary sexual
  characters of males is modeled for polygamous species in which males provide
  only genetic material to the next generation and females have many potential
  mates to choose among. Despite stabilizing natural selection on males,
  various types of mating preferences may create a runaway process in which the
  outcome of phenotypic evolution depends critically on the genetic variation
  parameters and initial conditions of a population. Even in the absence of
  genetic instability, rapid evolution can result from an interaction of
  natural and sexual selection with random genetic drift along lines of
  equilibria. The models elucidate genetic mechanisms that can initiate or
  contribute to rapid speciation by sexual isolation and divergence of
  secondary sexual characters.%
  }
  \field{issn}{0027-8424, 1091-6490}
  \field{number}{6}
  \field{pages}{3721\bibrangedash 3725}
  \field{title}{Models of speciation by sexual selection on polygenic traits}
