\entry{martens_ring_2007}{article}{}
  \name{author}{2}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Martens}{M.}%
     {Jochen}{J.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {PÃ¤ckert}{P.}%
     {Martin}{M.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \keyw{Circular overlap, Isolation by distance, Larus argentatus, Molecular
  genetic markers, Parus major, Phylloscopus trochiloides, Speciation by
  distance}
  \strng{namehash}{MJPM1}
  \strng{fullhash}{MJPM1}
  \field{labelyear}{2007}
  \field{sortinit}{M}
  \field{abstract}{%
  According to current theory, the splitting of a single species into two is
  best observed by a ring of intergrading populations which occupy a
  ring-shaped distribution area and whose terminal populations not only meet
  but overlap and co-occur without or with only little hybridization. The three
  most discussed examples in birds are revisited here. The great tit complex
  (Parus major s. l.) turned out to be an assemblage of four subspecies groups
  forming a secondary ring of population. The herring gull/lesser black-backed
  gull complex (Larus argentatus s. l.) forms a circumpolar circle of
  intergrading populations, but lacks the crucial cornerstone, the geographical
  overlap. The greenish warbler complex (Phylloscopus trochiloides s. l.) is
  close to the ideal ring species, but the ring is not complete and the
  Siberian zone of overlap needs further clarification and characterisation.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1016/j.jcz.2007.07.004
  \endverb
  \field{issn}{0044-5231}
  \field{number}{4}
  \field{pages}{315\bibrangedash 324}
  \field{series}{Special Issue: Phylogenetic Symposium 48th Phylogenetic
  Symposium on Historical Biogeography}
  \field{title}{Ring species â€“ Do they exist in birds?}
