  \strng{fullhash}{SADKDMMNBS1}
  \field{labelyear}{2013}
  \field{sortinit}{S}
  \field{abstract}{%
  Recent computational studies have shown that speciation can occur under
  neutral conditions, i.e., when the simulated organisms all have identical
  fitness. These works bear comparison with mathematical studies of clustering
  on neutral landscapes in the context of branching and coalescing random
  walks. Here, we show that sympatric clustering/speciation can occur on a
  neutral landscape whose dimensions specify only the simulated organismsâ€™
  phenotypes. We demonstrate that clustering occurs not only in the case of
  assortative mating, but also in the case of asexual fission; it is not
  observed in the control case of random mating. We find that the population
  size and the number of clusters undergo a second-order non-equilibrium phase
  transition as the maximum mutation size is varied.%
  }
