\entry{sexton_genetic_2014}{article}{}
  \name{author}{3}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Sexton}{S.}%
     {Jason~P.}{J.~P.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Hangartner}{H.}%
     {Sandra~B.}{S.~B.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Hoffmann}{H.}%
     {Ary~A.}{A.~A.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{climate change, environmental management, Isolation by distance,
  isolation by ecology, isolation by environment, swamping gene flow}
  \strng{namehash}{SJPHSBHAA1}
  \strng{fullhash}{SJPHSBHAA1}
  \field{labelyear}{2014}
  \field{sortinit}{S}
  \field{abstract}{%
  Gene flow among populations can enhance local adaptation if it introduces new
  genetic variants available for selection, but strong gene flow can also stall
  adaptation by swamping locally beneficial genes. These outcomes can depend on
  population size, genetic variation, and the environmental context. Gene flow
  patterns may align with geographic distance ({IBD}â€”isolation by distance),
  whereby immigration rates are inversely proportional to the distance between
  populations. Alternatively gene flow may follow patterns of isolation by
  environment ({IBE}), whereby gene flow rates are higher among similar
  environments. Finally, gene flow may be highest among dissimilar environments
  (counter-gradient gene flow), the classic â€œgene-swampingâ€ scenario. Here
  we survey relevant studies to determine the prevalence of each pattern across
  environmental gradients. Of 70 studies, we found evidence of {IBD} in 20.0\%,
  {IBE} in 37.1\%, and both patterns in 37.1\%. In addition, 10.0\% of studies
  exhibited counter-gradient gene flow. In total, 74.3\% showed significant
  {IBE} patterns. This predominant {IBE} pattern of gene flow may have arisen
  directly through natural selection or reflect other adaptive and nonadaptive
  processes leading to nonrandom gene flow. It also precludes gene swamping as
  a widespread phenomenon. Implications for evolutionary processes and
  management under rapidly changing environments (e.g., climate change) are
  discussed.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1111/evo.12258
  \endverb
  \field{issn}{1558-5646}
  \field{number}{1}
  \field{pages}{1â€“15}
  \field{shorttitle}{Genetic Isolation by Environment or Distance}
  \field{title}{Genetic isolation by environment or distance: Which pattern of
  gene flow Is most common?}
