\entry{thibert-plante_five_2009}{article}{}
  \name{author}{2}{}{%
    {{}%
     {Thibert-Plante}{T.-P.}%
     {X.}{X.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Hendry}{H.}%
     {A.~P.}{A.~P.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \list{language}{1}{%
    {en}%
  }
  \keyw{ecological speciation, Gene Flow, individual based modelling, selection
  against hybrids, selection against migrants, sexual preference}
  \strng{namehash}{TPXHAP1}
  \strng{fullhash}{TPXHAP1}
  \field{labelyear}{2009}
  \field{sortinit}{T}
  \field{abstract}{%
  We use an individual-based simulation model to investigate factors
  influencing progress toward ecological speciation. We find that environmental
  differences can quickly lead to the evolution of substantial reproductive
  barriers between a population colonizing a new environment and the ancestral
  population in the old environment. Natural selection against immigrants and
  hybrids was a major contributor to this isolation, but the evolution of
  sexual preference was also important. Increasing dispersal had both positive
  and negative effects on population size in the new environment and had
  positive effects on natural selection against immigrants and hybrids. Genetic
  divergence at unlinked, neutral genetic markers was low, except when
  environmental differences were large and sexual preference was present. Our
  results highlight the importance of divergent selection and adaptive
  divergence for ecological speciation. At the same time, they reveal several
  interesting nonlinearities in interactions between environmental differences,
  sexual preference, dispersal and population size.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1111/j.1420-9101.2008.01627.x
  \endverb
  \field{issn}{1420-9101}
  \field{number}{1}
  \field{pages}{109\bibrangedash 123}
  \field{title}{Five questions on ecological speciation addressed with
  individual-based simulations}
  \verb{url}
  \verb http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1420-9101.2008.01627.x/abs
  \verb tract
