\entry{van_doorn_origin_2009}{article}{}
  \name{author}{3}{}{%
    {{}%
     {van~Doorn}{v.~D.}%
     {G.~Sander}{G.~S.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Edelaar}{E.}%
     {Pim}{P.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
    {{}%
     {Weissing}{W.}%
     {Franz~J.}{F.~J.}%
     {}{}%
     {}{}}%
  }
  \strng{namehash}{DGSvEPWFJ1}
  \strng{fullhash}{DGSvEPWFJ1}
  \field{labelyear}{2009}
  \field{sortinit}{D}
  \field{abstract}{%
  Ecological speciation is considered an adaptive response to selection for
  local adaptation. However, besides suitable ecological conditions, the
  process requires assortative mating to protect the nascent species from
  homogenization by gene flow. By means of a simple model, we demonstrate that
  disruptive ecological selection favors the evolution of sexual preferences
  for ornaments that signal local adaptation. Such preferences induce
  assortative mating with respect to ecological characters and enhance the
  strength of disruptive selection. Natural and sexual selection thus work in
  concert to achieve local adaptation and reproductive isolation, even in the
  presence of substantial gene flow. The resulting speciation process ensues
  without the divergence of mating preferences, avoiding problems that have
  plagued previous models of speciation by sexual selection.%
  }
  \verb{doi}
  \verb 10.1126/science.1181661
  \endverb
  \field{number}{5960}
  \field{pages}{1704\bibrangedash 1707}
  \field{title}{On the origin of species by natural and sexual selection}
  \verb{url}
  \verb http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/326/5960/1704
  \endverb
  \field{volume}{326}
  \verb{file}
  \verb Full Text PDF:/home/ayana/.mozilla/firefox/b7fuqjsf.default/zotero/stor
